\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Ans-1. Bus Topology: All devices are connected to a single cable called a bus. Data travels along the bus to reach its destination. If the bus fails, the entire network goes down.\par
\par
Star Topology: All devices are connected to a central hub or switch. If one device fails, it doesn't affect the rest of the network, but if the hub or switch fails, the entire network goes down.\par
\par
Ring Topology: Each device is connected to exactly two other devices, forming a ring. Data travels in one direction around the ring. Failure of one device can disrupt the entire network.\par
\par
Mesh Topology: Every device is connected to every other device. This provides redundant paths for data to travel, increasing reliability but also complexity and cost.\par
\par
Tree Topology: Devices are arranged hierarchically, similar to a tree structure. This topology can be a combination of star and bus topologies. It's commonly used in large networks like the internet.\par
\par
Each topology has its advantages and disadvantages, and the choice depends on factors like cost, scalability, and fault tolerance.\par
