WAN stands for Wide Area Network, which covers a larger geographic area, often spanning multiple cities, countries, or continents. WANs connect LANs and other networks over long distances, enabling communication between geographically dispersed locations. The internet is the largest example of a WAN, connecting millions of devices worldwide. WANs often use technologies like leased lines, satellite links, or fiber optic cables to establish connections over long distances. They are typically operated and maintained by telecommunication companies or internet service providers (ISPs).\par
Ans-4. A switch operates by forwarding data packets between devices within a local area network (LAN). When a device connected to a switch sends data, the switch examines the destination MAC address of the data packet. It then consults its MAC address table to determine which port the destination device is connected to. \par
\par
If the MAC address is not found in the table, the switch broadcasts the data packet to all ports except the one from which it was received. When the destination device responds, the switch learns the MAC address of that device and adds it to its address table, associating it with the port from which the response was received.\par
\par
Subsequent data packets destined for that MAC address are then forwarded only to the port where the destination device is connected, reducing unnecessary network traffic. This process of forwarding packets based on MAC addresses enables efficient communication within the LAN.\par
