\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Ans-1. UTP (Unshielded Twisted Pair), MM (Multimode), and SM (Single Mode) are different types of Ethernet cabling used in networking. Here's a brief comparison:\par
\par
1. **UTP (Unshielded Twisted Pair)**:\par
   - **Advantages**: Cost-effective, easy to install, widely available.\par
   - **Disadvantages**: Limited distance (up to 100 meters), more susceptible to electromagnetic interference.\par
   - **Common Applications**: Ethernet networks in offices, homes, and small businesses.\par
\par
2. **MM (Multimode)**:\par
   - **Advantages**: Supports higher bandwidth over short distances, less expensive than single mode.\par
   - **Disadvantages**: Limited distance (typically up to 550 meters), higher attenuation.\par
   - **Common Applications**: Local area networks (LANs), data centers, short-distance connections.\par
\par
3. **SM (Single Mode)**:\par
   - **Advantages**: Supports higher bandwidth over longer distances, less susceptible to attenuation and signal degradation.\par
   - **Disadvantages**: More expensive than multimode, requires precise alignment of components.\par
   - **Common Applications**: Long-distance connections, telecommunications networks, backbone infrastructure.\par
\par
Choosing the appropriate type of Ethernet cabling depends on factors such as the required bandwidth, distance, budget, and environmental conditions.\par
