Ans-7. In the OSI Reference Model, encapsulation and decapsulation refer to the processes of adding and removing protocol headers as data travels through the layers of the model.\par
\par
1. **Encapsulation**:\par
   - When data is transmitted from one layer to another in the OSI model, each layer adds its own header (and sometimes trailer) to the data received from the layer above.\par
   - This process continues as the data moves down the layers, with each layer adding its own information, forming a protocol data unit (PDU).\par
   - The encapsulated data is then transmitted across the network.\par
\par
2. **Decapsulation**:\par
   - Upon receipt of data, the receiving device goes through the process of decapsulation, where each layer examines and removes its header (and trailer).\par
   - This process occurs in reverse order from the bottom layer to the top layer, with each layer extracting relevant information until the original data is recovered at the top layer.\par
\par
Encapsulation and decapsulation ensure that data is properly formatted and understood by devices at different layers of the OSI model as it traverses a network.\par
